  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "5 A fool despiseth his father's correction;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "   But he that regardeth reproof is prudent.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "We may with equal correctness translate: he acts prudently (after 1 Samuel 23:22); and, he is prudent (after Proverbs 19:25). We prefer, with Jerome, Venet., and Luther, the latter, against the lxx, Syr., and Targ., because, without a doubt, the יערם is so thought of at Proverbs 19:25 : the contrast is more favourable to the former. It is true that he who regardeth reproof is not only prudent, but also that he is prudent by means of observing it. With line first cf. Proverbs 1:7 and Proverbs 1:30, and with line second, Proverbs 12:1. Luther translates: the fool calumniates...; but of the meanings of abuse (properly pungere) and scorn, the second is perhaps here to be preferred.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "We may with equal correctness translate: he acts prudently (after ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Samuel 23:22",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "); and, he is prudent (after ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Proverbs 19:25",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). We prefer, with Jerome, Venet., and Luther, the latter, against the lxx, Syr., and Targ., because, without a doubt, the יערם is so thought of at ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Proverbs 19:25",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " : the contrast is more favourable to the former. It is true that he who regardeth reproof is not only prudent, but also that he is prudent by means of observing it. With line first cf. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Proverbs 1:7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
